42 A BILL
43 TO BE ENTITLED
44 AN ACT
45
46 Relating to youth sports organizations; to establish
47 the Youth Athlete Protection Act; to require the State
48 Department of Human Resources (DHR) to develop a model Youth
49 Athlete Protection Policy and mandatory reporter training for
50 youth sports coaches; to provide standards for the policy and
51 training relating to the prevention of child abuse; to require
52 youth sports organizations and local governments that offer
53 youth sports to implement a Youth Athlete Protection Policy;
54 to require coaches, including volunteers, to undergo a
55 criminal history background check and annual mandatory
56 reporter training to be eligible to act as a youth sports
Page 2

reporter training to be eligible to act as a youth sports
HB103 INTRODUCED
57 coach; to require youth sports organizations and certain local
58 governments to certify compliance with this act with DHR,
59 without which the entity is prohibited from offering youth
60 sports; and to require DHR to adopt rules.
61 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
62 Section 1. This act shall be known and may be cited as
63 the Youth Athlete Protection Act.
64 Section 2. For the purposes of this act, the following
65 terms have the following meanings:
66 (1) CHILD ABUSE. Physical abuse, sexual abuse or
67 exploitation, negligent treatment, or mental or emotional
68 abuse of an individual under 18 years of age.
69 (2) COACH. An individual employed or volunteering as a
70 coach, manager, or supervisor of a youth athletic activity.
71 The term does not include:
72 a. Any individual who occasionally assists with or
73 supports a youth athletic activity; or
74 b. Any employee or volunteer of a youth sports
75 organization that provides passing, general, or nominal
76 assistance with or support of a youth athletic activity.
77 (3) DEPARTMENT. The State Department of Human
78 Resources.
79 (4) LOCAL GOVERNMENT. A city, county, or other local
80 government that provides youth athletes the opportunity to
81 participate in scheduled competitive or recreational sporting
82 activities, whether individually or as a team.
83 (5) YOUTH ATHLETE. An individual under 18 years of age
84 participating in a youth sports organization.
Page 3

participating in a youth sports organization.
HB103 INTRODUCED
85 (6) YOUTH SPORTS ORGANIZATION. Any organization that,
86 as part of its core function, provides youth athletes the
87 opportunity to participate in scheduled competitive or
88 recreational sporting activities, whether individually or as a
89 team. The term does not include any of the following:
90 a. An organization that only offers sporting activities
91 incidental to a nonathletic program or lesson.
92 b. A public or private preK-12 school.
93 c. A licensed child-care facility, as defined in
94 Section 38-7-2, Code of Alabama 1975.
95 d. A public or private institution of higher education.
96 e. An organization that offers recreational sporting
97 activities only by providing the opportunity to participate in
98 unsupervised, unscheduled competitive or recreational sporting
99 events on a walk-in basis.
100 Section 3. (a) No later than January 1, 2027, the
101 department shall adopt and publish a model Youth Athlete
102 Protection Policy. The department shall consider national
103 standards relating to the prevention of child abuse, such as
104 those developed by the U.S. Center for SafeSport, when
105 developing the model policy. The model policy shall include,
106 but not be limited to, each of the following:
107 (1) Standards for prohibited conduct in youth sports.
108 The policy shall include a list of prohibited conduct by
109 parents, spectators, coaches, and youth athletes to prevent
110 the abuse of youth athletes. Prohibited conduct shall include,
111 but not be limited to, sexual abuse or misconduct, physical
112 abuse or misconduct, emotional abuse or misconduct, bullying,
Page 4

abuse or misconduct, emotional abuse or misconduct, bullying,
HB103 INTRODUCED
113 harassment, hazing, grooming behaviors, and any other
114 behaviors that risk the safety of youth athletes.
115 (2) A code of conduct for parents, spectators, coaches,
116 and youth athletes to follow. The code of conduct shall
117 include appropriate one-on-one interactions between players
118 and coaches and shall address topics including, but not
119 limited to, appropriate use of electronic communications
120 between adults and youth athletes, travel supervision
121 policies, and appropriate use of locker rooms and restrooms.
122 (3) A mandatory reporting policy for adults who have
123 knowledge of an act of prohibited conduct.
124 (b)(1) The department shall require each youth sports
125 organization and local government to annually certify
126 compliance with this act. The annual certification shall
127 include: (i) confirmation that the youth sports organization
128 or local government has a Youth Athlete Protection Policy that
129 complies with this act; and (ii) verification that each coach
130 has satisfactorily completed a criminal history background
131 check, completed mandatory reporter training, and been
132 provided a copy of the relevant Youth Athlete Protection
133 Policy. The department shall publish a list of all certified
134 youth sports organizations and local governments on the
135 department's website.
136 (2) A youth sports organization or local government
137 that is found to be out of compliance with the requirements of
138 this act shall immediately suspend the provision of youth
139 athletic activities until the entity provides documentation to
140 the department which verifies the entity has come into
Page 5

the department which verifies the entity has come into
HB103 INTRODUCED
141 compliance.
142 (c) The department shall develop a mandatory reporter
143 training program for coaches. The mandatory reporter training
144 shall include, but not be limited to, explanations of: (i) who
145 is a mandatory reporter and circumstances that must be
146 reported; (ii) the responsibilities of coaches as it relates
147 to the reporting of suspected child abuse; (iii) how to
148 respond to disclosures of child abuse or reports of behavior
149 that violate the prohibited conduct policy in a supportive and
150 appropriate manner that meets the mandatory reporting
151 requirements pursuant to state law; and (iv) child abuse
152 prevention strategies. In developing the mandatory reporter
153 training program, the department may use resources from
154 relevant national groups, such as the U.S. Center for
155 SafeSport.
156 (d) The department shall adopt rules to implement and
157 administer this act.
158 Section 4. (a)(1) No later than January 1, 2027, each
159 youth sports organization shall adopt a Youth Athlete
160 Protection Policy including, but not limited to: (i) standards
161 for prohibited conduct in youth sports; (ii) a code of conduct
162 for parents, spectators, coaches, and youth athletes; and
163 (iii) a mandatory reporting policy. The policy, at a minimum,
164 shall reflect the model policy developed by the department in
165 Section 3. Each youth sports organization shall provide a copy
166 of the Youth Athlete Protection Policy to all coaches employed
167 by or volunteering for the organization and parents of youth
168 athletes participating in a sport offered by that
Page 6

athletes participating in a sport offered by that
HB103 INTRODUCED
169 organization.
170 (2) Each youth sports organization shall require each
171 of its coaches to: (i) comply with the organization's
172 prohibited conduct policy; and (ii) annually complete
173 mandatory reporter training, as provided in Section 3.
174 (b)(1)a. Each youth sports organization shall require
175 each coach to obtain, prior to his or her employment or
176 acceptance as a volunteer, a criminal history background check
177 from the Alabama State Law Enforcement Agency (ALEA). ALEA may
178 provide the results of the criminal history background check
179 to the youth sports organization where the coach is seeking to
180 be employed or volunteer. The youth sports organization may
181 use the criminal history background check only for purposes of
182 making hiring or volunteer decisions, and the results of the
183 criminal history background check are otherwise confidential.
184 b. Youth sports organizations may rely on the results
185 of a criminal history background check when making hiring and
186 volunteer decisions. Youth sports organizations are immune
187 from any civil liability relating to the hiring of a coach or
188 acceptance of a coach as a volunteer, except where the youth
189 sports organization: (i) knows the information relating to the
190 coach's criminal history background check is false; or (ii)
191 acts with reckless disregard concerning the veracity of that
192 information.
193 (2) No youth sports organization may hire or accept as
194 a volunteer a coach if a criminal history background check
195 performed on that individual shows that he or she has been
196 convicted of, pled nolo contendere to, or has received a
Page 7

